### Encapsulation

Encapsulation hides internal implementation details and controls access to an object's data. Dart achieves this through privacy and access control.

### Private Members

In Dart, privacy is library-level, not class-level. Members prefixed with `_` are private to the library (file).

```dart
class BankAccount {
  String _accountNumber; // Private field
  double _balance;       // Private field

  BankAccount(this._accountNumber, this._balance);

  // Public methods to access private data
  double getBalance() => _balance;

  void deposit(double amount) {
    if (amount > 0) {
      _balance += amount;
    }
  }

  bool withdraw(double amount) {
    if (amount > 0 && amount <= _balance) {
      _balance -= amount;
      return true;
    }
    return false;
  }
}
```

### Getters and Setters for Control

```dart
class Temperature {
  double _celsius;

  Temperature(this._celsius);

  // Getter
  double get celsius => _celsius;

  // Setter with validation
  set celsius(double value) {
    if (value < -273.15) {
      throw ArgumentError('Temperature cannot be below absolute zero');
    }
    _celsius = value;
  }

  // Computed getter
  double get fahrenheit => _celsius * 9 / 5 + 32;
}
```

### Public and Private in Practice

```dart
// person.dart
class Person {
  String _name;    // Private to this file
  int _age;        // Private to this file
  final String id; // Public

  Person(this._name, this._age, this.id);

  String get name => _name;
  int get age => _age;

  set name(String value) {
    if (value.isNotEmpty) _name = value;
  }
}
```

### Benefits of Encapsulation

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Data hiding | Internal state is protected |
| Validation | Control what values can be set |
| Flexibility | Change internals without affecting users |
| Maintainability | Clear API boundary |

### Library Visibility

```dart
// library.dart
library my_library;

// Public: accessible everywhere
int publicVar = 10;

// Private: accessible only within this library
int _privateVar = 20;
```

> **Key Point:** Dart's `_` prefix makes members library-private, not class-private. The privacy applies at the file level. Use getters and setters to control access to private fields.

codeExample:
class User {
  String _username;
  String _email;
  bool _isActive;

  User(this._username, this._email, this._isActive);

  String get username => _username;
  String get email => _email;
  bool get isActive => _isActive;

  set email(String value) {
    if (value.contains('@')) {
      _email = value;
    } else {
      throw ArgumentError('Invalid email');
    }
  }

  void deactivate() {
    _isActive = false;
  }

  void activate() {
    _isActive = true;
  }
}

void main() {
  var user = User('alice', 'alice@example.com', true);
  print(user.username);
  user.deactivate();
  print('Active: ${user.isActive}');
}
